<Project
  pretitle="Side project"
  title="HomeLab"
  subtitle="Self-hosting on Proxmox, Docker and Kubernetes"
  link="..."
>
  <p>
    I have had a server cluster already long before starting my studies. Over
    the years the hardware, software and cluster style has changed a lot.
    Initially, I only had a simple off-the-shelve <strong>NAS</strong>, by now I
    am running a <strong>multi-node cluster</strong> build from used but modern hardware.
    Each nodes runs <strong>Proxmox Virtual Environment</strong> in a quorum cluster
    configuration, with various <strong>LXC Container</strong> and <strong
      >Virtual Machines</strong
    >. All workloads are synchronized on local storage and backed up to a <b
      >NAS</b
    >.
  </p>
  <br />
  <p>
    On-top of <strong>Proxmox</strong> I am also running a <b
      >multi-node Kubernetes cluster</b
    > for various <strong>OCI</strong> based workloads. Initially, the Kubernetes
    cluster was running on <strong>Bare-Metal</strong> using <strong
      >Longhorn</strong
    >, <strong>MetalLB</strong>, <strong>ServiceLB</strong> and <strong
      >CertManager</strong
    >. However, the whole cluster was moved into <strong>Proxmox</strong> to take
    advantage of both worlds. Some of these workloads are now also handled by <strong
      >Proxmox</strong
    >, resulting in my own little <strong>private cloud</strong>. I have been
    using <strong>K0s</strong>, <strong>KubeAdm</strong>, <strong
      >KubeSpray</strong
    >, but mostly (and currently) <strong>K3s</strong>.
  </p>
</Project>
